  "slug": "thunderbolts-is-marvels-return-to-form-is-it-too-late",
  "title": "‘Thunderbolts*’ Is Marvel’s Return to Form. Is It Too Late?",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins",
    "Mallory Rubin"
  ],
  "published": "2025-05-02",
  "runtimeMin": 93,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey, Amanda Dobbins, and Mallory Rubin talk through 'Thunderbolts*,' the film that broke a five-year Marvel cold streak for them, from its creaky first 45 minutes to the group-hug climax, then argue over whether a return to form arrives too late to matter.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Thunderbolts*'",
      "note": "the superfan, the cynic, and the skeptic all show up",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Thunderbolts*",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Jake Schreier ('Beef', 'Robot & Frank') directs; Eric Pearson and Joanna Calo ('The Bear') write; Andrew Droz Palermo shoots, and the editor cut 'Minari,' an indie-pedigree crew Marvel leaned into with an A24-style trailer. All three land in the same place: creaky, exposition-heavy first 45 minutes, then it clicks once David Harbour's Red Guardian shows up. Florence Pugh's Yelena carries it; Sebastian Stan's Bucky 'blows almost everybody else off the screen' barely trying. Lewis Pullman (Steven Yeun's replacement) plays Bob/the Sentry/the Void, a superhero and supervillain in one body whose power is literally depression. Amanda dissents on Julia Louis-Dreyfus as Val. Praised for real locations and practical effects over volume-stage 'video game vomit'; the climax is a group hug, and the New Avengers stinger sets up 'Doomsday' and 'The Fantastic Four: First Steps'. The 36th MCU film and the last of Phase Five."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
